<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-10-11T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-10-11T19:00:00-05:00" n="877" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d877">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">693.002/1130: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-10-11T19:00:00-05:00">October
                                    11, 1941—7 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>241. Your 414, October 8, 10 a.m., Chinese Maritime Customs. Department
                            concurs in the views expressed in your telegram under reference and
                            desires that the American Consul General at Shanghai make to the
                            Inspector General of Customs the statement suggested in the first
                            substantive paragraph of your telegram.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Chungking, repeated to Shanghai. Shanghai repeat to Tokyo.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>